{{short description|Statistical significance threshold for genetic associations}}
In [[genome-wide association studies]], '''genome-wide significance''' (abbreviated '''GWS''') is a specific threshold for determining the [[statistical significance]] of a reported [[association (statistics)|association]] between a given [[single-nucleotide polymorphism]] (SNP) and a  given [[trait (biology)|trait]]. The most commonly accepted threshold is [[p-value|''p'']] < 5 × 10<sup>−8</sup>, which is based on performing a [[Bonferroni correction]] for all the independent common SNPs across the [[human genome]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Xu |first=ChangJiang |last2=Tachmazidou |first2=Ioanna |last3=Walter |first3=Klaudia |last4=Ciampi |first4=Antonio |last5=Zeggini |first5=Eleftheria |last6=Greenwood |first6=Celia M. T. |last7=the UK10K Consortium |date=April 2014 |title=Estimating Genome-Wide Significance for Whole-Genome Sequencing Studies: Genome-Wide Significance for Rare Variants |journal=Genetic Epidemiology |language=en |volume=38 |issue=4 |pages=281–290 |doi=10.1002/gepi.21797 |pmc=4489336 |pmid=24676807}}</ref> If a ''p''-value is found to be lower than this threshold in a genome-wide association study, the [[null hypothesis]] of no true SNP-association will typically be rejected.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Roeder |first=Kathryn |last2=Wasserman |first2=Larry |date=November 2009 |title=Genome-Wide Significance Levels and Weighted Hypothesis Testing |journal= Statistical Science|volume=24 |issue=4 |pages=398–413 |doi=10.1214/09-STS289 |issn=0883-4237 |pmc=2920568 |pmid=20711421}}</ref> However, there has been some criticism of this threshold, with a 2012 study suggesting that a significant number of associations with ''p''-values just above this threshold are genuine, replicable associations. The authors of this study concluded that their finding "...suggests a possible relaxation in the current GWS threshold."<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Panagiotou |first=Orestis A |last2=Ioannidis |first2=John P A |last3=for the Genome-Wide Significance Project |date=February 2012 |title=What should the genome-wide significance threshold be? Empirical replication of borderline genetic associations |journal=International Journal of Epidemiology |language=en |volume=41 |issue=1 |pages=273–286 |doi=10.1093/ije/dyr178 |pmid=22253303 |issn=0300-5771|doi-access=free }}</ref> More recently, it has been suggested that the conventional threshold should be modified to take into account the increasing prevalence of low-[[allele frequency|frequency]] genetic variants in genome-wide association studies.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Fadista |first=João |last2=Manning |first2=Alisa K. |last3=Florez |first3=Jose C. |last4=Groop |first4=Leif |date=August 2016 |title=The (in)famous GWAS P-value threshold revisited and updated for low-frequency variants |journal=European Journal of Human Genetics |volume=24 |issue=8 |pages=1202–1205 |doi=10.1038/ejhg.2015.269 |issn=1476-5438 |pmc=4970684 |pmid=26733288}}</ref>

